04044nam a22005295i 9780520969223DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2018    cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209692237 a10.1525/97805209692232doi  a(DE-B1597)520302  a(OCoLC)1002302972  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0020002bisacsh1 aBoehm, Ryan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.10aCity and Empire in the Age of the Successors :bUrbanization and Social Response in the Making of the Hellenistic Kingdoms /cRyan Boehm. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (273 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart One: Urbanization and the Imperial Framework -- t1. Imperial Geographies: City, Settlement, and Ideology in the Formation of the Hellenistic Kingdoms -- t2. Urbanization and Economic Networks -- tPart Two. Cult, Polis, Empire: The Religious and Social Dimensions of Synoikism -- t3. Civic Cults between Continuity and Change -- t4. Consensus, Community, and Discourses of Power -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tSubject Index -- tIndex Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the chaotic decades after the death of Alexander the Great, the world of the Greek city-state became deeply embroiled in the political struggles and unremitting violence of his successors' contest for supremacy. As these presumptive rulers turned to the practical reality of administering the disparate territories under their control, they increasingly developed new cities by merging smaller settlements into large urban agglomerations. This practice of synoikism gave rise to many of the most important cities of the age, initiated major shifts in patterns of settlement, and consolidated numerous previously independent polities. The result was the increasing transformation of the fragmented world of the small Greek polis into an urbanized network of cities. Drawing on a wide array of archaeological, epigraphic, and textual evidence, City and Empire in the Age of the Successors reinterprets the role of urbanization in the creation of the Hellenistic kingdoms and argues for the agency of local actors in the formation of these new imperial cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 0aCity-stateszGreecexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2016-2019z978311063851608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2018z978311066767708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520969223423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520969223.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-063851-6  DG and UP eBook Package 2016-2019c2016d2019  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066767-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles